Occasionally I come across an app that's so good that I regret not having started using it long ago. HiPER Calc Pro is one such app. After trying many calculator apps, here's one that does everything I need (maths not sums) - and more importantly makes proper use of a touchscreen device, rather than just emulating a traditional calculator. What I mean is that certain keys bring up menus of additional functions and options. That might not sound like much, but it makes for a great user interface!!

When I'm doing calculations, I really appreciate NOT having to round things off. Doing so is less exact and can lead to problems. This is, by far, the best you can get. And using it on a tablet let's you see all the options on-screen at once. But when on a phone screen, they've managed quite well to fit so many features in. Bravo!

I have 5 calculators installed on my phone, and this one just becale my default. The reason for this is as follows: I am a mathematician - graduated from the Math faculty of the University of Waterloo in the 80s, and have been working as a mathematician since. I am also o a student and enthusiast of maths history. My central joy in maths is the fact that it is ultimately flexible. While there are conventions (such as the PEMDAS order of operations) - these are merely conventions, and can be redefined for any context at hand. So - when one of the unending memes on FaceBook arguing over the order of operations came up with: does 6√∑2(2+1) equal 1 or 9, I wanted to see what my various calculators were assuming about the precedence of the obelus symbol for divide (√∑) in the expression. HiPER Calc popped up a settings option: """ Operand Grouping: Select how parts of the expression should be grouped: ( ) Weak - Treat i√∑2œÄ as (1/2)œÄ - or - ( ) Strong -Treat i√∑2œÄ as 1/(2œÄ) - You can change this setting in Settings/Expression """ Well... I was just tickled. I paid for the pro version of the App, and made it my default.

if you add percentage, it is added to a base. 10% is 0.1. If you add 10% to it, the calculator adds 10% to the base which is 0.1 and that's why the result is 0.11. If you want just to add percentage points, just enter 10 + 10 and you get the result 20.

My advice to anyone who wants to look around for a better calculator app is...don't waste your time, there isn't one. I don't give 5 star ratings lightly. An app has to really impress me, exceed my expectations, and have no significant flaws. With this one, it's a no-brainer. I've tried dozens of the top rated calculator apps over the course of a few years and this one blows them all away. It has pretty much everything you could possibly want in a calculator app and a lot more. Just about every time I think "Wouldn't it be nice if it had such-and-such feature?", it turns out that it already does. It's highly customizable, well-organized, and intuitive. However, if you want a basic calculator without too many bells and whistles, you can easy switch to a clean and simple mode. It's also nice when the app that's #1 in functionality is the most nicely designed. The default skin is based on Radio Shack scientific calculators, but  sleeker. The developer pays close attention to user feedback and is constantly working on improving an app that's already tops in its category. Multiple times when I've seen a good suggestion in the reviews, it was implemented in the very next version.
